Create a blank plot

ggplot()

Plot mpg data set

mpg or miles per gallon dataset comes with R installation.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = cty)) +
  geom_point()

Boxplot

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(y = cty)) +
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = manufacturer, y = cty)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Bar plot

##  $ hwy         : int [1:234] 29 29 31 30 26 26 27 26 25 28 ...

table(mpg$class)
## 
##    2seater    compact    midsize    minivan     pickup subcompact        suv 
##          5         47         41         11         33         35         62
ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = class)) +
  geom_bar()

dplyr::count(mpg, class)
## # A tibble: 7 x 2
##   class          n
##   <chr>      <int>
## 1 2seater        5
## 2 compact       47
## 3 midsize       41
## 4 minivan       11
## 5 pickup        33
## 6 subcompact    35
## 7 suv           62
ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = class)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "blue",
           alpha = 0.5,
           color = "red",
           size = 1) 

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = cty)) +
  geom_bar()

class_freq <- dplyr::count(mpg, class)
ggplot(data = class_freq,
       mapping = aes(x = class, y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

ggplot(data = class_freq,
       mapping = aes(x = class, y = n)) +
  geom_col() # This is equal to geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Histogram

Bar graph for a continuous variable

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = cty)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 12,
                 fill = "navy",
                 color = "white")

Jitter plot

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = manufacturer, y = cty)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2)

set.seed(999)
ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = class, 
                     y = cty,
                     color = class)) +
  geom_jitter()

set.seed(999)
ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = class, 
                     y = cty,
                     color = class)) +
  geom_violin() +
  geom_jitter()
